If we agree that removing one serious crime from the chain of command doesn't harm good order and discipline, let's treat all serious, non-military crimes the same way. Vanessa Guillén was murdered — she and her family also deserve justice.

For nearly a decade, the Department of Defense told me that removing the decision to prosecute sexual assault from the chain of command would undermine good order and discipline.

Let me be clear: I won't allow this bill to be watered down or minimized. I won't allow the voices of survivors to be silenced. And I will not stop fighting until the Military Justice Improvement and Increasing Prevention Act is given the full floor vote that it deserves.

It's time to pass this bill — and we have the votes to do it. Every day this week, I've stood and asked for #MJIIPA to receive a full vote on the floor of the Senate.

But every single day, I've been refused.

#MJIIPA removes the decision to prosecute serious crimes out of the chain of command and gives it to trained military prosecutors. It's supported by survivors, service members, commanders, and legal experts. And now we have 65 bipartisan Senate cosponsors.

Over the last few years, the rate of sexual assault in the military has soared to historic highs. But the rate of prosecutions and convictions has plummeted. Our military justice system is failing our service members — and they're demanding action.

The Military Justice Improvement and Increasing Prevention Act has 65 bipartisan cosponsors — a filibuster-proof majority.

So why hasn't it been passed yet? Here's what's going on:

We have an obligation to our colleagues, our staff, and the brave members of the Capitol Police to investigate exactly what led to the deadly violence of January 6th. This shouldn't be a partisan issue. We can't move forward without accountability or justice.

#MJIIPA has 65 bipartisan cosponsors — a filibuster-proof majority. We could pass this bill today and secure justice for survivors of military sexual assault. It's time to give this bill the full floor vote it deserves. https://t.co/8MsaTxbbon
